---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import LoopsDiagram from '../components/LoopsDiagram.astro';
---
<Base>
  <h1>myalicia</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    An AI teammate that grows into the shape of the person it serves.
    The tangible example of <a href="https://humorphism.com">humorphism</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    For decades, design taught us that good software adapts to the human.
    Buttons look like buttons. Trash cans look like trash cans. The medium
    bent toward us. Then for a long stretch, we forgot — we built tools
    that asked humans to bend the other way, to learn keyboard shortcuts,
    to memorize syntax, to think like the machine.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Humorphism</strong> is the design philosophy that says: AI doesn't
    have to keep that bargain. It can take a shape that fits a particular
    person, and grow with them. <strong>myalicia</strong> is what that looks
    like as code you can run on your own machine.
  </p>

  <hr class="rule" />

  <h2>Three depths of attention</h2>

  <p>
    myalicia is built around three relationship loops, each running at a
    different cadence, all reading from and writing to a shared memory
    substrate — your vault, your notes, your archetype. Awareness compounds
    because three different cadences of reflection are constantly
    metabolizing your input into structure.
  </p>

  <div class="figure">
    <LoopsDiagram />
    <p class="caption">The three relationship loops over a shared memory substrate.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Listen</h3>
  <p>
    <em>Seconds.</em> Be present in the conversation in front of you. Cheap,
    fast model. The only loop most AI products have.
  </p>

  <h3>Notice</h3>
  <p>
    <em>Minutes to hours.</em> Catch patterns across moments. Triggered by
    events: you finished a book, you closed a project, you came back from a
    trip. Mid-tier model, wider context, asynchronous.
  </p>

  <h3>Know</h3>
  <p>
    <em>Days to weeks.</em> Come to know the person, over time. Scheduled
    autonomous reflection. Most expensive, runs on its own, produces
    synthesis the user didn't ask for but is glad to have.
  </p>

  <hr class="rule" />

  <h2>For designers and builders</h2>

  <p>
    The contribution surface here is what we call <strong>awareness primitives</strong> —
    small, opinionated modules that turn some slice of life into structured
    memory the loops can metabolize. A reading-pattern primitive. A
    calendar-rhythm primitive. A relationship-graph primitive.
  </p>

  <p>
    Don't think of contributions as "writing code." Think of them as
    <em>designing perception</em>. That framing is what humorphism asks of
    designers in the agentic era: stop designing chatbots, start designing
    relationships.
  </p>

  <hr class="rule" />

  <h2>Try it</h2>

  <p>
    <code>pip install myalicia &amp;&amp; myalicia init</code>
  </p>

  <p>
    The init flow is more than configuration — it's a guided introduction
    to relationship-shaped AI. Each setup step is paired with a one-screen
    explanation of which loop it activates and why.
  </p>

  <p>
    <a class="cta" href="https://github.com/mrdaemoni/myalicia">View on GitHub →</a>
  </p>
</Base>
